  <!-- ── Function of Quench Oil ── -->
  <h2 id="function-of-quench-oil">Function of Quench Oil in Heat Treatment</h2>

  <p>
    Quench oil serves a critical function in metallurgical heat treatment. When heated metal parts are immersed in the quench tank, the oil provides <strong>rapid, controlled cooling</strong> that determines the final metallurgical properties of the workpiece.
  </p>

  <p>
    During the quenching process, the oil performs several key functions:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Rapid Cooling:</strong> Extracts heat from the metal at a controlled rate, enabling the desired microstructural transformation (e.g., martensite formation in steel hardening)</li>
    <li><strong>Recrystallization Control:</strong> The cooling rate controls the crystal structure of the metal, directly determining hardness, tensile strength, and ductility</li>
    <li><strong>Oxidation Prevention:</strong> The oil blanket prevents atmospheric oxygen from reaching the hot metal surface, minimizing scale formation and surface decarburization</li>
    <li><strong>Uniform Heat Transfer:</strong> Clean quench oil provides consistent heat extraction across the entire part surface, preventing distortion and soft spots</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Maintaining quench oil cleanliness is not simply an oil-life issue &mdash; it directly affects the metallurgical quality of every part processed through the quench tank.
  </p>

  <!-- ── Effects of Contamination ── -->
  <h2 id="effects-of-contamination">Effects of Quench Oil Contamination</h2>

  <p>
    Quench oil becomes contaminated through normal heat treatment operations. The primary contaminants include:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Carbon and Soot:</strong> Thermal decomposition of the quench oil at the metal-oil interface generates carbon particles and soot that accumulate in the oil</li>
    <li><strong>Rust and Iron Oxide:</strong> Scale and oxide layers flake off workpieces during quenching, introducing iron particles into the oil</li>
    <li><strong>Metal Scales:</strong> Heat treatment scale from the workpiece surface breaks free during the quench and settles throughout the system</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    These contaminants cause a cascade of operational problems when left unchecked:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Uneven Heat Treatment:</strong> Contaminant particles insulate portions of the workpiece surface, causing inconsistent cooling rates that result in soft spots, uneven hardness, and part distortion</li>
    <li><strong>Clogged Filters:</strong> Conventional bag and cartridge filters clog rapidly in quench oil service, requiring frequent changes and creating disposal costs</li>
    <li><strong>Heat Exchanger Fouling:</strong> Sludge deposits on heat exchanger surfaces reduce cooling efficiency, causing quench oil temperatures to rise above specification</li>
    <li><strong>Increased Oil Degradation:</strong> Contaminants accelerate thermal and oxidative breakdown of the quench oil, shortening its useful life</li>
    <li><strong>Surface Defects:</strong> Carbon and sludge particles adhering to quenched parts cause surface staining and defects that require secondary finishing operations</li>
  </ul>

