  <!-- ── Operation ── -->
  <h2 id="operation">How a Quench Oil Centrifuge Operates</h2>

  <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row gap-6 items-start mb-6 not-prose">
    <div class="flex-1 min-w-0 prose prose-lg max-w-none">
      <p>The quench oil centrifuge uses <strong>disc stack separation technology</strong> to continuously purify quench oil. The centrifuge bowl, containing a stack of closely spaced conical discs, spins at high speed to generate the centrifugal force required for fine particle separation.</p>

      <h3>Separation Process</h3>

      <p>Contaminated quench oil enters the centrifuge through a central feed tube and is distributed between the conical discs in the <a href="/disc-stack-centrifuge-parts/">disc stack</a>. Under intense centrifugal force (7,000+ Gs), contaminant particles &mdash; being denser than the oil &mdash; migrate outward toward the bowl wall, while clean oil moves inward and exits through the light-phase discharge.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="md:w-[42%] shrink-0">
      <img
        src="/images/quench-oil-centrifuge/Quench-Oil-Centrifuge-e1627306972157.webp"
        alt="Quench Oil Centrifuge"
        width="600" height="450"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-lg w-full h-auto"
      />
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>
    The disc stack dramatically increases the effective settling area within the bowl. Each pair of adjacent discs creates a thin oil channel where the particle travel distance to the capture surface is measured in millimeters. This enables removal of particles as small as <strong>0.5 microns</strong> &mdash; far finer than any practical filtration system.
  </p>

  <h3>Automatic Sludge Ejection</h3>

  <p>
    Separated sludge accumulates in the bowl periphery. At programmable intervals, the <strong>self-cleaning bowl opens hydraulically</strong>, ejecting the accumulated sludge in a fraction of a second. The bowl immediately recloses and separation resumes without interruption. This automatic discharge cycle eliminates manual cleaning and allows <strong>24/7 unattended operation</strong>.
  </p>

  <h3>Centripetal Pump Discharge</h3>

  <p>
    Clean oil exits the centrifuge through a built-in <strong>centripetal pump</strong> (paring disc), which converts the rotational energy of the oil into discharge pressure. This eliminates the need for a separate discharge pump and ensures the centrifuge output can be returned directly to the quench tank or reservoir under pressure.
  </p>

  <p>
    The centrifuge operates in a <strong>kidney loop</strong> configuration &mdash; continuously drawing oil from the quench tank, cleaning it, and returning purified oil. This arrangement maintains oil cleanliness without interfering with production quenching operations.
  </p>

